groups on the ground but direct talks between

14:13.519 --> 14:19.892 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the two of them. And it now has the imprimatur
of the U.N. Security Council, and Ban Ki-moon,

14:19.926 --> 14:22.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the secretary general, committed to help implement
it.

14:22.995 --> 14:26.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: So, there'd been a lot of countries
working toward this, but there are four major

14:26.933 --> 14:30.069 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
players and smack-dab in the middle of all
this is Bashar al-Assad.

14:30.103 --> 14:36.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARNER: That's right. The major division among
many concerns his future. On one side, you've

14:36.109 --> 14:42.949 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
got the United States and the Gulf states
who began all this wanting Assad gone as soon

14:42.982 --> 14:48.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as possible, and both have supported opposition
groups on the ground in different ways. But

14:48.755 --> 14:55.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the other side you've got Russia and Iran,
both of them regard Syria, and Syria is a

14:55.294 --> 15:01.134 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
client state for different reasons. Both of
them have sent military assistance weapons

15:01.167 --> 15:07.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
advisors, even fighters, and in Russia's case
bombs, to try to shore him up.

15:07.073 --> 15:09.942 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: And there's tensions between
the United States and Russia.

15:09.976 --> 15:13.579 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARNER: Yes, that's very true. Then you
have another cross-cutting tension between

15:13.613 --> 15:19.018 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the U.S. and Russia, which would be for influence
in this process. For a long time, Russia wasn't

15:19.051 --> 15:23.089 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very involved and then it inserted itself
in September by beginning this bombing, and

15:23.122 --> 15:26.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
won itself a place at the table, because they
want influence over the outcome.

15:26.692 --> 15:28.628 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: And Saudi Arabia and Iran have
their tensions.

15:28.661 --> 15:33.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARNER: They certainly do. And, in fact, that's
part of the knob of all of this. Saudi Arabia,

15:33.499 --> 15:40.206 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leader of the Sunni states in this region,
and Iran, of course, Shiite state, huge historical

15:40.239 --> 15:43.442 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rivalry for primacy in this region.

15:43.476 --> 15:46.979 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: All right. So, what do peace
players all actually get over their disagreements

15:47.013 --> 15:48.581 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and agree to?

15:48.614 --> 15:52.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARNER: Which really is incredible. I think
it's two things, Hari. One is threat of

15:52.585 --> 15:56.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
international terrorism. Even the Chinese
foreign minister this to reporters today,

15:56.789 --> 16:01.661 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we've got to get the process going because
of threat of international terrorism.

16:01.694 --> 16:08.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have come to the conclusion that they
can never take on ISIS until the boil of the

16:08.634 --> 16:15.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Syrian conflict, until they launch that boil.
That remember was the original, not only attracter

16:15.608 --> 16:22.415 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but incubator of all of the thousands of foreign
fighters coming in, helping beef up this al

16:22.448 --> 16:28.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Qaeda in Iraq that became ISIS, helping them
establish them this caliphate in the ungoverned

16:28.921 --> 16:33.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
portion of eastern Syria and roll on into
Iraq and they recognize there's no way to

16:33.626 --> 16:35.361 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
take them on.

16:35.394 --> 16:40.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The second thing that they've agreed on is
that, militarily, it can't be solved. Every

16:40.466 --> 16:44.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one of them, these four countries, has supported
different groups on the ground and they now

16:44.704 --> 16:50.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
all realize they have been sucked into a quagmire.
There is no military resolution, has to be

16:50.610 --> 16:52.211 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
political.

16:52.245 --> 16:55.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: All right. So, one thing at the
dead center of all this is Assad. The next

16:55.314 --> 17:00.953 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
steps here, this agreement doesn't mention
him by name, which is one of those central

17:00.987 --> 17:02.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tensions you mentioned.

17:02.622 --> 17:06.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WARNER: Absolutely, and they had to do it
that way because the differences remain and

17:06.125 --> 17:10.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
so they had to finesse it. They talk about
a political transition. The United States

17:10.396 --> 17:15.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
believes if you have a transition to an inclusive
nonsectarian government which is its language

17:15.234 --> 17:21.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
