23:02.381 --> 23:04.016 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOODRUFF: A few years ago in Syria.

23:04.049 --> 23:09.488 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: I mean, that was -- and so -- and
there is a retreat from that. And, he, you

23:09.521 --> 23:15.661 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
know, whether through bad luck or just bad
judgment or bad information, he's equated

23:15.694 --> 23:22.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ISIS to how much geography it holds, and that
isn't the fear and the fear isn't whether

23:22.301 --> 23:28.807 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in fact they do own more acreage or dominate
more acreage, or more towns and cities, quite

23:28.841 --> 23:38.284 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bluntly, to Americans. It's the potential
for real damage and anxiety in this country.

23:38.317 --> 23:43.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then he made the reference to them as
junior varsity. I mean, it was the sense that,

23:43.489 --> 23:50.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you know, he didn't understand or didn't
at least project an understanding of the real

23:50.496 --> 23:55.834 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
risk that these folks presented.

23:55.868 --> 24:02.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What he has come from now is the Republicans
do not have any difference in -- with the

24:02.508 --> 24:05.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
exception of Lindsey Graham who says we have
--

24:05.344 --> 24:07.346 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOODRUFF: You mean the candidates.

24:07.379 --> 24:08.947 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
SHIELDS: Yes.

24:08.981 --> 24:10.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROOKS: I'm not sure I agree with that.
I mean, the speeches that were given -- the

24:10.783 --> 24:13.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Obama speeches, compare to the Hillary Clinton
speeches, Hillary Clinton laid out a comprehensive

24:13.619 --> 24:18.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
plan with multi-prongs on how to deal with
Syria, which is much more aggressive than

24:18.123 --> 24:23.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
anything Obama is doing. Marco Rubio and Jeb
Bush were not as specific as Clinton but basically

24:23.896 --> 24:28.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it overlaps a lot of what Clinton with a few
extra things. And Obama hasn't even done that

24:28.767 --> 24:31.804 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
far. He hasn't laid out a comprehensive plan.

24:31.837 --> 24:39.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Those three, Clinton, Rubio, Bush, have basically
said the Sunnis themselves have to take out

24:39.278 --> 24:46.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ISIS with American -- Western air support,
and that means defanging Assad, because the

24:46.719 --> 24:52.958 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sunnis won't do it as long as they're being
barrel bombed.

24:52.991 --> 24:56.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, that's a strategy. And Obama hasn't
likely gone there even. And so, there is been

24:56.395 --> 24:59.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a vacuity as to how he's talking about the
issue.

24:59.398 --> 25:04.570 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: But how do you -- how does the president
acknowledge that without giving into what's

25:04.603 --> 25:12.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now described as a climate of fear where everything
is something to be afraid of and Americans

25:12.211 --> 25:15.614 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
should be really rattled by what's happened
in San Bernardino?

25:15.647 --> 25:20.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: Well, I mean, I think a good part
of it is the tone, the sense of resoluteness

25:20.619 --> 25:27.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or not. I mean, whether it's Churchill or
whatever. I mean, words do matter.

25:27.659 --> 25:34.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But where I disagree with David is, you know,
they ask the Republicans whether it's Bush

25:34.233 --> 25:40.506 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or Rubio, oh, yes, yes, we do -- we need drones.
We need drones. The president used drones

25:40.539 --> 25:45.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more than anybody in the history of human
kind, with much criticism from the international

25:45.811 --> 25:47.513 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
community.

25:47.546 --> 25:51.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need more airstrikes. We are using airstrikes.
We need Special Forces. There are Special

25:51.917 --> 25:55.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Forces also, without revealing American secrets.

25:55.387 --> 25:59.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But nobody, nobody, with the exception of
Lindsey Graham is saying, let's go -- I

26:00.025 --> 26:03.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mean, Mike Huckabee says, yes, we should send
troops but I can't tell you how many because

26:03.862 --> 26:10.335 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that would be revealing. But I mean, Rubio,
they all talk tough, but they really don't

26:10.369 --> 26:12.237 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
come out.

26:12.271 --> 26:17.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I agree with you, Hillary Clinton is the one
Democrat who does come off as more commander-in-chief-ish.

26:17.376 --> 26:19.111 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
BROOKS: Yes.

26:19.144 --> 26:23.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Well, I want to ask about the Democrats
because, typically, people say when it comes

26:23.048 --> 26:26.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to national security, it plays to the strength
of the Republicans. But, David, you're saying

26:26.452 --> 26:28.487 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hillary is holding her own in that.

26:28.520 --> 26:29.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BROOKS: Yes. I mean --

26:29.288 --> 26:31.123 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOODRUFF: What about Bernie Sanders?

26:31.156 --> 26:34.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROOKS: I still think it generally helps Republicans.
But if any Democrat can maintain parity, it's

26:34.660 --> 26:36.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to be Hillary Clinton. People trust
her on that.

26:36.895 --> 26:40.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But this is a crushing blow. The shift in
the news has been a crushing blow to Bernie

26:40.599 --> 26:43.435 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sanders. There are other good things have
happened to him. He's got a base of support.

26:43.469 --> 26:45.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's gotten some endorsements. But it's
just a crushing blow.

26:45.671 --> 26:52.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think this and some of the Black Lives Matter
movement are just -- don't play to the strengths.

26:52.177 --> 26:58.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, as long as the economy is number one,
inequality is number one, that's in his wheelhouse.

26:58.450 --> 27:02.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But especially with the attention shifting
to security, that's far out of the wheelhouse.

27:02.254 --> 27:03.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOODRUFF: Do you agree?

27:03.856 --> 27:06.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: Yes, there is two profiles to the
party. I mean, the Democrats are the more

27:06.592 --> 27:09.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
nurturing party, the party of social justice.

27:09.495 --> 27:14.867 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You ask people, who's better on education?
The Democrats. Who's better on climate change

27:14.900 --> 27:19.171 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or preserving the environment? Democrats.
Who's better for widows and orphans? Democrats.

27:19.204 --> 27:24.142 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Who's better on national security and terrorism?
The Republicans. Republicans are seen as historically

27:24.176 --> 27:28.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tougher. Whether in fact this is logical,
rational, these are the perceptions. So, the

27:28.313 --> 27:30.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Republicans have a double-digit advantage
on it.

27:30.816 --> 27:38.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, you could go through and look for
the papers that -- observing any of those

27:38.757 --> 27:43.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the stage and the only one you find is
Lindsey Graham, but they all talk a very tough

27:43.328 --> 27:44.396 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
game.

27:44.429 --> 27:46.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: But you agree Bernie Sanders has
been hurt?

27:46.398 --> 27:48.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

27:48.066 --> 27:50.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: Bernie Sanders -- this is not Bernie
Sanders' natural area. He was chairman of

27:50.235 --> 27:56.308 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
veterans committee, but, no, national security
is not his strength. And Hillary Clinton is

27:56.341 --> 28:01.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seen as somebody with steel in her spine.
She's seen as tough. She's seen as experienced.

28:01.113 --> 28:05.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She may not be seen as totally honest and
she may not be seen as absolutely likable,

28:05.584 --> 28:07.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but she is seen as tough, and experienced
and smart.

28:07.486 --> 28:11.857 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Well, there is another Democratic
issue that's come up just today, this breach

28:11.890 --> 28:15.928 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the Democrats voter parties -- voter database.

28:15.961 --> 28:23.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Sanders campaign recognized that there
was a technical glitch. They had access for

28:23.535 --> 28:28.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
half an hour or more. They say they didn't
do anything with that information they had

28:28.206 --> 28:33.612 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
access to. The Clinton campaign says they
did. The DNC has now shut down the Sanders'

28:33.645 --> 28:35.213 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
camp access.

28:35.247 --> 28:38.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is this -- I mean, right now, the Sanders
camp is suing the DNC, the Clinton people

28:38.617 --> 28:41.987 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are holding news conferences. Is this -- what
does this add up to, David?

28:42.020 --> 28:46.959 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROOKS: Well, the first bad part for the Sanders
campus, they saw a window and grabbed it,

28:46.992 --> 28:50.729 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and a couple -- at least a couple of staffers
did. Not just one. A couple of staffers grabbed

28:50.762 --> 28:53.432 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some information they probably didn't have
access to.

28:53.465 --> 28:57.336 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nonetheless, I do not think that people are
going to see Bernie Sanders as a corrupt man.

28:57.369 --> 28:59.004 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
SHIELDS: Yes.

28:59.037 --> 29:02.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROOKS: That is not his weak spot. So, I don't
think he'll be particularly hurt by this.

29:02.608 --> 29:06.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What could happen on the other hand is the
Clinton campaign is now in the midst of a

29:06.178 --> 29:12.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
massive overreaction, on Twitter and this
press conference, massively overreacting and

29:12.818 --> 29:17.889 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
making it look like they are the bully establishment.
And I don't know -- on the Republican side,

29:17.923 --> 29:22.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there is such a fervent anti-establishment
feel, that if somebody had a chance to run

29:22.227 --> 29:24.196 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
against the RNC for that candidate, golden.

29:24.229 --> 29:28.934 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm not sure the Democrats are that anti-establishment.
But it sure gives Bernie Sanders an opening

29:28.967 --> 29:33.605 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to say, the big powers in Washington, along
with Hillary Clinton are sealing up this game

29:33.639 --> 29:37.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and trying to shut me down, and I think that's
fertile for him.

29:37.776 --> 29:39.778 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SHIELDS: Let me agree with David.

29:39.811 --> 29:45.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bernie Sanders, 2 million donors. Average
contribution is $30. Nobody else is even remotely

29:46.018 --> 29:49.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
close to that. It's a remarkable campaign.
It's gotten bigger crowds in the Republican

29:49.421 --> 29:53.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
front runner. I mean, he's really been,
it's a remarkable candidacy.

29:53.392 --> 30:02.367 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this -- Judy, the window is open, all
right? The curtains are up and the pretty

30:02.401 --> 30:09.207 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
girl is standing there in her night gown and
the Sanders people look in. They weren't breaking

30:09.241 --> 30:13.979 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in, they weren't trying to get in but it's
available. They look at the information for

30:14.012 --> 30:15.714 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
30 minutes, OK?

30:15.747 --> 30:19.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Clinton people, the last thing in the
world they want to be talking about is electronic

30:19.551 --> 30:23.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
data and computers with the Clinton email
problem.

30:23.321 --> 30:28.160 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And with Debbie Wasserman, the chair of the
Democratic National Committee having limited

30:28.193 --> 30:30.762 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the debates to five debates now --

30:30.796 --> 30:31.430 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOODRUFF: Democratic.

30:31.463 --> 30:32.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SHIELDS: Democratic debates.

30:32.230 --> 30:33.799 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOODRUFF: Right.

30:33.832 --> 30:38.570 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: One-half -- not even one-half as
the Republicans. It was open, free party.

30:38.603 --> 30:42.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Saturday night when -- Saturday night, the
lowest TV night of the week, that's when

30:42.774 --> 30:43.709 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they want it --

30:43.742 --> 30:45.410 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Another one coming up tomorrow night.

30:45.444 --> 30:48.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: Tomorrow night, to limit it. Looks
like they tilted already in Hillary Clinton's

30:48.980 --> 30:50.816 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
favor.

30:50.849 --> 30:54.920 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And now she's depriving Bernie Sanders' campaign
of the one thing they have which is the information?

30:54.953 --> 31:00.158 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, their campaign was a door-to-door,
person-to-person campaign and they're going

31:00.192 --> 31:04.596 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to deprive them of that? I mean, it just looks
like David against Goliath, boy, I'm rooting

31:04.629 --> 31:06.331 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for David.

31:06.364 --> 31:09.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: So, what started out as an accusation
against the Sanders camp you're saying could

31:09.534 --> 31:12.104 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
end up helping Sanders?

31:12.137 --> 31:18.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROOKS: Yes, but the question is how much
anti-establishment is in the Democratic Party.

31:18.677 --> 31:22.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Maybe they don't mind the establishment. Yes,
I sort of like the people that run my party.

31:22.114 --> 31:24.750 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Republicans don't think that. They hate the
people that run their party. But I'm not

31:24.783 --> 31:26.384 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sure about the Democrats.

31:26.418 --> 31:30.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SHIELDS: Yes, I just think -- I think bullying
and unfairness. And they've already had

31:30.689 --> 31:37.796 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
criticism from Tulsi Gabbard, the Democratic
vice chair of the committee, criticized Wasserman

31:37.829 --> 31:42.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for the limited number of debates to favor
and to tilt in the advantage of Hillary Clinton,

31:42.868 --> 31:47.172 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
already. So, boy, I just think -- I think
the Clinton people are playing it dumb.

31:47.205 --> 31:50.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: This may have increased the audience
for tomorrow night, Democratic.

31:50.675 --> 31:52.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SHIELDS: Let's hope.

31:52.277 --> 32:02.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Mark Shields, David Brooks, thank
you.

32:02.120 --> 32:04.890 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(MUSIC)

32:04.923 --> 32:11.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: As the holidays approach, it is
a time of the year when many are more focused

32:11.763 --> 32:17.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on trying to help those in need. We have a
look at a program that helps those on hard

32:17.903 --> 32:21.339 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
times learn new skills and find jobs.

32:21.373 --> 32:22.407 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

32:22.440 --> 32:24.109 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

32:24.142 --> 32:28.346 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: This is where rubber
meets the road, when you learn about management

32:28.380 --> 32:30.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and how to take care of your kitchen.

32:30.348 --> 32:33.385 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN, PBS NEWSHOUR CORRESPONDENT:
Morning class work at a well-established if

32:33.418 --> 32:39.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
unlikely culinary school in our nation's capital;
the students, mere weeks from graduation.

32:39.324 --> 32:45.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: So, who can give me the
first principle of a hazard analysis critical

32:45.197 --> 32:46.865 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
control point?

32:46.898 --> 32:50.335 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: It's new territory for most of them.
Some are recently homeless, others recovering

32:50.368 --> 33:03.715 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from drug and alcohol addiction, newly-released
from prison or chronically unemployed.

33:03.748 --> 33:08.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Located in the basement of a large homeless
shelter just blocks from the White House and

33:08.553 --> 33:14.826 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
U.S. capitol, D.C. Central Kitchen is the
nation's largest community kitchen. Its full-time

33:14.860 --> 33:20.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
professional staff, helped out by a steady
stream of volunteers, puts out 5,000 meals

33:20.398 --> 33:26.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a day, which are sent to homeless shelters,
schools, half-way houses and other non-profits

33:26.238 --> 33:28.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the area.

33:28.740 --> 33:33.879 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Much of the kitchen's output is prepared from
donated ingredients -- produce, canned goods,

33:33.912 --> 33:38.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
meat and fish that local restaurants and food
retailers would otherwise throw away.

33:38.550 --> 33:41.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE CURTIN, D.C. CENTRAL KITCHEN CEO: We
do so many things, all of which however are

33:41.486 --> 33:46.057 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
focused on and around the idea that waste
is wrong. And that waste could be --

33:46.091 --> 33:46.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BROWN: Waste is wrong?

33:46.958 --> 33:48.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CURTIN: Waste is wrong.

33:48.660 --> 33:54.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
As a nation, almost 40 percent of the food
that we produce of the day goes in the garbage.

33:54.132 --> 33:57.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And yet, people are hungry. There's something
really, really wrong with that.

33:57.936 --> 34:04.376 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: For D.C. Central Kitchen CEO Mike Curtin,
reversing food waste is one-half the kitchen's

34:04.409 --> 34:05.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
two-pronged mission.

34:06.011 --> 34:08.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CURTIN: And while we're doing that, we're
training men and women who are coming out

34:08.647 --> 34:14.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of incarceration, battling addiction, surviving
abuse, homelessness and unemployment for jobs

34:14.686 --> 34:19.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in this hospitality business. We're trying
to bring these two things together around

34:19.457 --> 34:24.195 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the same table in a way that's going to create
positive economic growth and opportunity for

34:24.229 --> 34:25.764 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
everyone.

34:25.797 --> 34:28.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: It's better that we
start from here, because if we try to pile

34:28.199 --> 34:31.536 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
(ph) this way, we're going to get tired
because we're pushing all of this --

34:31.569 --> 34:36.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: That means the culinary program and
its students are deeply embedded in the kitchen's

34:36.408 --> 34:41.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
daily activities. It can be demanding, even
a little intimidating at times.

34:41.579 --> 34:43.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Say "thank you, chef,"
for what?

34:43.515 --> 34:45.917 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: Thank you, chef, for
straightening out my life.

34:45.951 --> 34:47.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MAEL: Any time.

34:47.652 --> 34:53.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: There is a kind of tough-love at work
here, and often, a bond of shared experience.

34:53.391 --> 34:54.659 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You know what this is like.

34:54.693 --> 34:55.493 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARIANNE ALI, DIRECTOR, CULINARY TRAINING
PROGRAM: Oh, absolutely.

34:55.527 --> 34:56.962 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BROWN: Tell me what you came from.

34:56.995 --> 35:00.899 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALI: I had a 20-year rough bout with heroin.

35:00.932 --> 35:04.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: Marianne Ali is director of the culinary
training program.

35:04.502 --> 35:08.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALI: I would say crack saved my life, because
if it wasn't, I could have probably been

35:08.740 --> 35:15.180 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a heroin addict for longer. But crack takes
you down so fast, and I was at the bottom

35:15.213 --> 35:17.048 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of rock bottom.

35:17.082 --> 35:22.654 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: She eventually got clean, went to culinary
school, then got a job with D.C. Central Kitchen.

35:22.687 --> 35:24.422 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What did you think you could bring to it?

35:24.456 --> 35:30.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALI: I knew that I could serve as an example,
you know, hopefully; that people would look

35:30.795 --> 35:38.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at me and say, "If she did it, then maybe
perhaps there's a chance", because recovery

35:38.403 --> 35:40.038 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is all, it's a lot about hope.

35:40.071 --> 35:45.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: But making a new start takes more than
knife skills and hope. Many of the changes

35:45.310 --> 35:49.514 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
required of these students are personal and
take place on the inside.

35:49.547 --> 35:54.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALI: How do I deal with my anger? How do I
deal with somebody who is an authority? How

35:54.853 --> 36:01.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do I deal with juggling, having to go see
my P.O. and being here on time and doing what

36:01.659 --> 36:05.296 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I need to do -- it's a lot to have to balance.

36:05.330 --> 36:11.002 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: Students Tamyra Hill and Terrell Nicholson
agree. She is a mother of three who's struggled

36:11.036 --> 36:12.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to find work in recent years.

36:12.737 --> 36:17.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TAMYRA HILL, CULINARY STUDENT: For me, the
hardest time is just being outside the classroom

36:17.475 --> 36:21.212 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and finding time to study and finding time
to prep for exams. Like I said, I have children;

36:21.246 --> 36:24.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have to help them with their homework, and
then after they are in bed I have to take

36:24.682 --> 36:29.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the time to study for myself. So, for me,
that has been -- I won't say a struggle,

36:29.821 --> 36:33.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but it has been the part I have to constantly
work on.

36:33.658 --> 36:38.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: Nicholson was released from prison
not long before he came to the program.

36:38.063 --> 36:42.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TERRELL NICHOLSON, CULINARY STUDENT: I never
had a problem getting a job; it was keeping

36:42.367 --> 36:49.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it that I had a problem with because I was
going interview and get a job, and I would

36:49.407 --> 36:55.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
work. But I would allow other influences to
keep me from staying focused.

36:55.847 --> 37:02.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: Teaching chefs Daniela Hurtado (ph)
and Anand Shantam see the challenges some

37:02.120 --> 37:05.824 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of their students face, trying to move from
one way of life to another.

37:05.857 --> 37:12.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANAND SHANTAM, CHEF INSTRUCTOR: If you've
got someone who's been unemployed, gone through

37:12.964 --> 37:19.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
addiction. It's hard to come into a learning
situation where they now have to get disciplined,

37:19.404 --> 37:28.813 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be on time, take constructive feedback and
not see it as criticism, but see it as an

37:28.847 --> 37:30.448 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
opportunity to grow.

37:30.482 --> 37:33.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIELA HURTADO, CHEF INSTRUCTOR: Having the
right attitude. People will bump into you

37:33.885 --> 37:40.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
yes, the right attitude. People will bump
into, and sometimes you are defensive. And

37:40.758 --> 37:46.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from the environment that they are coming
from, sometimes it's kind of harsh. So, it's

37:46.865 --> 37:51.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not personal; those are some of the challenges
that we try to deal with here.

37:51.136 --> 37:57.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: The culinary training program runs
14 weeks -- including a four-week internship

37:57.609 --> 38:03.581 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in local restaurants and three weeks of guided
job-search -- and it boasts a stunning 80

38:03.615 --> 38:05.683 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
percent graduation rate.

38:05.717 --> 38:07.852 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Still, not everyone makes it.

38:07.886 --> 38:11.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CURTIN: We might find that they're not quite
ready. They haven't hit a place in their life

38:11.256 --> 38:20.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where they see this as a best path to take.
Addiction is a brutal mistress, and sometimes,

38:20.365 --> 38:23.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it takes longer for some people to work their
way out of it than others.

38:23.835 --> 38:28.139 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: The students we talked to felt they
were beginning to find their feet, and they

38:28.173 --> 38:29.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
credited the kitchen.

38:29.874 --> 38:32.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NATHANIEL TROLLER, CULINARY STUDENT: I have
three kids, so I want to be the father figure

38:32.343 --> 38:36.447 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for them so they won't chase the same things
I went through in my life.

38:36.481 --> 38:38.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LANDRELL JORDAN, CULINARY STUDENT: Coming
in here taught me how to get into the roots

38:38.149 --> 38:44.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of where my anger is coming from; the pain,
it taught me how to deal with it out, as you

38:45.023 --> 38:48.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
talk about, get it out, feel better about
myself, you know? And here I am now, I'm

38:48.426 --> 38:50.528 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
doing positive, something that I love.

38:50.562 --> 38:55.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: What do you think is the key to making
it work? Why does it work?

38:55.233 --> 38:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CURTIN: Because we meet people where they
are. We're really not here to judge what people

38:58.770 --> 39:02.540 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have done, or where they've been, or the decisions
they've made. We're here to talk about the

39:02.574 --> 39:07.545 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
future and to take what people have innately
and give that a little context and say this

39:07.579 --> 39:10.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is what you can do. If you work hard, if you
commit yourself, if you dedicate yourself

39:10.882 --> 39:13.418 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to this, you can be successful.

39:13.451 --> 39:19.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: And with 90 percent of the kitchen's
students finding jobs upon graduation, that

39:19.057 --> 39:22.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
formula seems to be working.

39:22.727 --> 39:30.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
From downtown Washington, D.C., I'm Jeffrey
Brown for the PBS NEWSHOUR.

39:30.668 --> 39:35.306 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

39:35.340 --> 39:44.382 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: The blockbuster successful British
TV series, "“Downton Abbey"” begins its

39:44.415 --> 39:51.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sixth and final season here on PBS next month.
We got an inside look at the show, its creator

39:51.189 --> 39:54.626 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and explore why so many Americans love it.

39:54.659 --> 39:56.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

39:56.461 --> 40:04.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: The music is instantly recognizable,
as is the tail -- that's Isis, the dog -- both

40:04.769 --> 40:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
part of the opening credits to the blockbuster
British television drama, "Downton Abbey."

40:10.508 --> 40:15.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the past five years, the Crawley family
and their servants have entertained us, and

40:15.747 --> 40:22.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in January, the drama begins its sixth and
final season on PBS.

40:22.053 --> 40:28.726 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The last chance for a few more one-liners
from the dowager countess of Grantham, played

40:28.760 --> 40:36.734 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
exquisitely by Dame Maggie Smith.

40:36.768 --> 40:44.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And surely, one final calamity to beset lady's
maid Anna and her butler husband Bates.

40:44.375 --> 40:51.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The mastermind of this runaway success is
Sir Julian Fellowes; also an actor, film director,

40:51.049 --> 40:55.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and, in his spare time, a conservative member
of Britain's House of Lords.

40:55.753 --> 41:01.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, "Downton Abbey" coming to an end, is this
-- are you saying goodbye to a dear friend?

41:01.893 --> 41:03.661 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Or is it just -- have you already moved on?

41:03.695 --> 41:07.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JULIAN FELLOWES, CREATOR: No, I wouldn't
say I have moved on. I mean, "Downton" has

41:07.398 --> 41:13.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
been an extraordinary milestone. You've
spent a lot of time in this industry, working

41:13.171 --> 41:17.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very hard on things that don't do terribly
well, the public doesn't get them or whatever,

41:17.408 --> 41:21.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and then you suddenly ring the bell. It's
been fantastic.

41:21.779 --> 41:28.986 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Fantastic beyond belief, becoming
the top-rated PBS drama of all time.

41:29.020 --> 41:36.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Globally, "Downton" airs in over 220 countries
with a worldwide audience of 120 million people.

41:36.427 --> 41:41.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FELLOWES: I never think it's a good idea to
outstay your welcome. And it seems right to

41:41.532 --> 41:44.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leave, so, I don't think we're doing the wrong
thing, but it's been a happy time.

41:44.535 --> 41:50.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: A happy time with roots in a book
by American historian Carol Wallace, author

41:50.808 --> 41:55.179 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of "To Marry an English Lord," Sir Julian's
inspiration for the series.

41:55.213 --> 41:59.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CAROL WALLACE, AUTHOR, "“TO MARRY AN ENGLISH
LORD"”: When he had been asked by the producers

41:59.083 --> 42:08.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to write a series about English aristocrats,
he had been reading "To Marry an English Lord."

42:08.559 --> 42:14.732 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he said he thought it was all very well
for these heiresses to marry, but then what

42:14.766 --> 42:21.038 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
happened to them 20 years later when they
were -- I think he put it -- "freezing in

42:21.072 --> 42:28.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a house in Cheshire, aching for Long Island"?
And that, of course, Cora Grantham's dilemma,

42:28.780 --> 42:30.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there she is right there.

42:30.548 --> 42:35.820 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Wallace's book tells the true stories
of young American heiresses who left the U.S.

42:35.853 --> 42:41.826 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the late 1800s to shop for husbands in
England. Their money attracted down at the

42:41.859 --> 42:46.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
heels aristocrats who had titles and little
else.

42:46.063 --> 42:49.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What would he have seen in these stories,
in this history?

42:49.200 --> 42:56.441 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WALLACE: I think what Julian saw, the source
of the drama is exactly the asymmetry of expectation

42:56.474 --> 43:01.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- what these American girls thought marriage
was going to be and what it turned out to

43:01.045 --> 43:08.286 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be, and how their American expectations kind
of, trailed along with them and formed their

43:08.319 --> 43:15.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relationships and their ideas of marriage
as they would 2030 years later.

43:15.293 --> 43:22.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: The American girl of "Downton Abbey",
Cora Crawley, countess of Grantham, is played

43:22.099 --> 43:25.536 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by Elizabeth McGovern.

43:25.570 --> 43:35.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH MCGOVERN, ACTOR: I am shocked at
how sad I do feel to say goodbye to people

43:35.613 --> 43:44.489 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH MCGOVERN, ACTOR: I am shocked at
how sad I do feel to say goodbye to people

43:44.522 --> 43:52.497 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and houses and the family. It's been a definite
life-changing kind of time for all of us.

43:52.530 --> 43:54.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOODRUFF: In what way?

43:54.265 --> 44:02.106 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MCGOVERN: Well, we've all been through something
that just felt it's had a big impact on our

44:02.140 --> 44:05.209 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
personal lives and we have been in it together.

44:05.243 --> 44:11.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: The drama began in 1912, the day
after the sinking of the Titanic, and has

44:11.549 --> 44:18.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
proceeded through World War I, the Spanish
flu and the jazz age. Season six is set in

44:18.256 --> 44:26.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
1925 and opens to find many formerly rich
families abandoning the life "Downton" epitomizes,

44:26.063 --> 44:32.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
unable to afford the expanse. Like the character
she plays, McGovern is married to an Englishman

44:32.403 --> 44:34.505 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and lives in the U.K.

44:34.539 --> 44:37.742 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How is it different from other television
series?

44:37.775 --> 44:44.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MCGOVERN: Well, the one extraordinary difference
is that every word is written by one man.

44:44.315 --> 44:50.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't know of any other television show
that works that way. And I, to this day, find

44:50.755 --> 44:52.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it absolutely mindboggling.

44:52.590 --> 44:56.961 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Julian Fellowes did not intend on
being the sole writer.

44:56.994 --> 45:03.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FELLOWES: I was actually thrilled to get other
people to do it, but, for some reason which

45:03.801 --> 45:11.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't really explain, the series seem to
have quite a distinctive voice. And we did

45:11.242 --> 45:16.047 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
try, at the beginning, to see if we could
get other people to replicate that voice.

45:16.080 --> 45:22.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we tried with very good people. But it
seemed that if we wanted to sustain this particular

45:22.386 --> 45:23.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
voice, it had to be me.

45:23.988 --> 45:30.595 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REBECCA EATON, MASTERPIECE: It's coming
from his heart, his experience, his passion.

45:30.628 --> 45:37.068 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: PBS' Masterpiece presents "Downton
Abbey" in the United States, and Rebecca Eaton

45:37.101 --> 45:39.270 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is the program's executive producer.

45:39.303 --> 45:44.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EATON: There's a lot of heart in it. There's
a lot of generosity. These are characters

45:44.141 --> 45:49.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who are taking care of each other. And that
is a lot of who Julian is.

45:49.280 --> 45:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FELLOWES: We dealt with all the characters
very evenly.

45:56.654 --> 46:01.025 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We didn't say, "The family are the important
characters and the servants are the comic

46:01.058 --> 46:06.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relief, or servants are gallant on suffering
but the family is horrible," all of which

46:06.330 --> 46:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
would have been a treatment in an earlier
period.

46:08.666 --> 46:14.538 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: You give equal time to everyone,
so, in a way you're looking at that age old

46:14.572 --> 46:23.014 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
struggle that we are dealing with today in
2015 about inequality, discrimination and

46:23.047 --> 46:25.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the rest of it. And you bring your own set
of views to that.

46:25.850 --> 46:30.521 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FELLOWES: It's this business of entitlement,
that a child of the middle or upper caste

46:30.554 --> 46:35.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is brought up to believe that certain things
are sort of their right, that this is the

46:35.426 --> 46:40.231 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
way they will live. Whereas other people are
brought up to feel like outsiders -- "oh,

46:40.264 --> 46:44.101 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're overreaching, so that's not for the
likes of us", and all this stuff still goes

46:44.135 --> 46:45.736 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on.

46:45.770 --> 46:50.441 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It does interests me. It shocks me and it
drives me mad when people try to pretend it

46:50.474 --> 46:55.446 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doesn't exist, because, of course, it doesn't
exist for them. There are millions of people

46:55.479 --> 47:00.017 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who are being cheated of their proper destiny
because it does still exist.

47:00.051 --> 47:04.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Do you think "Downton" contributes
to the conversation, to the discussion of

47:04.689 --> 47:06.257 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that?

47:06.290 --> 47:11.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FELLOWES: I hope it contributes. I mean, I
think in our society, particularly for the

47:11.195 --> 47:18.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
"me-me-me generation," there is a kind of
underlined solipsism in so many of us that

47:18.235 --> 47:25.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the only life that's really happening is our
own. And everyone else's life is sort of dependent

47:25.342 --> 47:27.078 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on our life.

47:27.111 --> 47:36.654 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One of the important things about drama is
to remind the viewer that everyone is 100

47:36.687 --> 47:41.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
percent at the center of their own life. That
there is no life being lived under that roof

47:41.158 --> 47:48.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that is more or less important; that Mary
or Daisy, what happens to them is just as

47:48.999 --> 47:55.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
important. And that's why we have equal dramatic
weight for all the stories, to show that.

47:55.673 --> 48:00.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: What do you think will give people
great joy and excitement and surprise, in

48:00.111 --> 48:04.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
